bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Since 1938, the Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington (now the Jewish Community Relations Council of Greater Washington) has served the Jewish community by responding to important issues and speaking out on behalf of the community's concerns. It aims to promote the cultural, social, economic, and philanthropic interests and advance the national and spiritual aspirations of Jewish people.

On March 6, 1938 twenty-five presidents of Jewish organizations in the greater Washington area joined together to consider the formation of a communal council capable of addressing the needs of the Jewish community in an organized and cohesive manner. From this initial meeting evolved the Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington, D.C. (It was known as the Jewish Community Council of Washington until the late 1940's). They created the organization to respond to certain immediate social concerns, including the fate of Jews in Nazi Germany, as well as the specter of rising anti-Semitism in the United States. On 31 January 1939, the group held its first formal meeting and 73 representatives from 39 organizations approved a Constitution and By-Laws.

Rabbi Solomon Metz, Hymen Goldman, and Rabbi Isadore Breslau were among the founders of the Council and served in succession as its first three presidents. Their contributions shaped the Council, along with those of Isaac Franck, who from 1948 to 1973 was its Executive Director and its guiding force.

Born in Russia in 1909, Franck came to America as a teenager and studied at New York University, Columbia University, and Harvard University, eventually earning a Ph.D in philosophy from the University of Maryland in 1966.

When Franck arrived in Washington to take over the Council in 1948, there were approximately 60 Jewish organizations participating. When he retired in 1973, there were over 170. During Franck's time the Council grew dramatically and worked with other organizations and faiths to address a wide range of social and political problems. Among these were issues of civil rights and desegregation, education, assistance to the poor, and Home Rule for the District of Columbia.
After Frank's retirement, in the 1970's and 1980's, the concern for the treatment of Soviet Jews and issues of war and peace in Israel and the Middle East occupied much of the Council's agenda.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection consists primarily of papers and printed matter, including meeting minutes, memoranda, correspondence, reports, and press releases. It also contains a number of photographs and a single audio cassette. The material ranges in date from 1937 to 1988, but the bulk of the material ranges from 1965 to 1979.

The Administrative Files series contains documents such as the Constitution and By-Laws of the organization, meeting minutes, and budget reports, which provide a continuous record of the Council from 1938 to 1983. The Committees, Task Forces, and Working Groups series comprises almost half of the total collection, and contains material dealing with the plight of Soviet Jewry, Israel's relationship with countries in the Middle East, and committees formed to address social conditions within the Greater Washington Area. The Other Constituent Organizations series deals with organizations which address many of the same concerns the Council does, and which worked in collaboration with the Council in a number of ways. The Subject Files series covers a wide range of topics ranging from anti-Semitism to the Vietnam War. The Oversized Series contains a small number of materials too large to be kept in their original folders. The series arrangement established by the agency has been maintained, with the exception of moving materials on Isaac Franck from the Subject Files series to the Administrative Files series.

The collection contains significant material on various committees, namely the Executive Committee, the Intergroup Relations Committee, and the Soviet Jewry Committee. It contains less documenting the history of the Council's early years in the late 1930's and 1940's. In addition, with the exception of Isaac Franck, the collection lacks detailed information on the organization's members and presidents.

The Records of the Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington were donated to the Gelman Library in 1986. Additional accessions were accepted in 1988 and 1992, and future accessions are expected. The Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington and individuals whose work forms part of this collection retain literary property rights. The main offices of the Council are currently located in Rockville, Maryland. Previously, they were located in downtown Washington, D.C.
Please note: this collection contains unprocessed materials. Ask staff about using this material.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into six series: Administrative files; Committees, task forces, and working groups; Other constituent organizations; Subject files; Oversized material; and Accession 2007.

did.unittitle: Administrative files

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series documents the founding and early years of the Council. Topics include: delegate assembly, executive committee, organizational committees, and the Isaac Franck files. The bulk of the collection materials in this series are agendas, memoranda, minutes, lists of delegates/presidents, resolutions, reports, addresses, news releases, newsletters, correspondence, Constitution and By-Laws of the Council, budgets/expenditures, photographs, and newspaper clippings.

The material in this series is dated from 1938 to 1985, with the bulk spanning the years 1950 to 1975. Isaac Franck is included in this series because as Executive Director of the JCCGW from 1948 to 1973, he was instrumental in shaping its focus and direction in the formative years and beyond. These records are very useful in examining the evolution of the Council's organization, representation, and focus. Of particular interest in this series are the early Constitution and By-Laws. Also of note are the files of Isaac Franck, which include his personal correspondence and writings from 1942 to 1973, among them materials related to his 1957 trip to post-war Germany.

Committees, task torces, and working groups

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is comprised of seven separate committees, task forces, and working groups within the Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington over the years. These groups include: bicentennial commission, community task force, holocaust committee, intergroup relations, urban affairs/social action committee, Soviet Jewry, Israel and the Middle East, and miscellaneous committees, task forces. (The Soviet Jewry and Israel and the Middle East committees producing the most files.) The bulk of the materials comprising this series are reports, budgets, memoranda, correspondence, photographs, booklets, minutes, newsletters, and transcripts. The material in this series is dated from 1941 to 1983, with the bulk of it covering the years from 1968 to 1979. The committees and task forces contained in this series demonstrate the commitment of the local Jewish community to social and political issues both at home and abroad.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains a diverse range of subject files with materials including memoranda, correspondence, reports, booklets, clippings, minutes, handbills, and excerpts from the Congressional Record. There is also an audio cassette. Some folders contain items in Hebrew, German, and French.

This content of this series reflects the variety of issues the Council has addressed. For instance, it contains information on African American/Jewish relations from the civil rights era and the urban crisis of 1960's, including the Council's efforts to work with black leaders such as Martin Luther King, Jr. in dealing with fundamental problems facing minorities. The relationship of Jews and Catholics is also covered in this series, especially the implications of the Vatican II Ecumenical Council in 1964, which called for the exchange of mutual knowledge and brotherly dialogue between Christians and Jews. Other subjects of interest include files regarding humane slaughtering legislation from the 1940's to 1960's as it affected the Jewish practice of shechita, as well as a proposed national Jewish population survey in the mid-1960's.

The following presidents of the Jewish Community Council of Greater Washington are also represented in the subject files: Solomon Metz (1938-1943); Hymen Goldman (1943-1949); Isadore Breslau (1949-1953); Aaaron Goldman (1953-1957); Albert Arent (1957-1961); Joel Wolfson (1961); Richard Lyon (1961-1965); Louis Grossberg (1965-1969); and Seymour Wolf (1969-1972).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials that were too large to fit in their companion boxes. The nine items include: a 1947 reprint from The New Leader, on how to deal with the anti-Semitic Gerald L.K. Smith; a 1949 poster of newspaper clippings related to religion in public schools; a 1952 Courier (a publication of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization); a 1955 reprint from Look magazine on the position of Jews in America; a newspaper insert, "The Jericho March," related to Soviet Jewry in the 1960's; a handbill for a rally on behalf of Soviet Jews in 1971; a 1974 fund raising poster from ProJeCt, a Washington interreligious alliance; a newspaper board game from 1975 concerning emigration of Soviet Jews; and a 1981 poster from an audio-visual presentation on Jerusalem.
